comment: Extremely repetitive. Extremely repetitive. Lectures are borrring. But he is trying and is actually a good person. Probably could be fine without showing up to class once.

Extremely poor teaching ability. Overly repetitive on simple topics, but moves too quickly on difficult topics. Appears not to know material very well; misspeaks and corrects himself regularly. Little correlation between the textbook used for problem sets and the material taught in class. Course lacked any context or overarching point. Avoid.
He is an awful professor, avoid at all costs. Never explains his material clearly, and will fail you for phrasing things slightly differently than he did on your essays and exams.
Repeated his points in class over and over again. Can't read his comments at all on essays. Interest level dropped after taking the class.
He really does try... but is doesn't give a completely clear picture of the subjects he is teaching.  Overly pedantic
european.
Don't need to go to class, just need to be smart. He's very smart and very cool and very approachable

It's hard to describe Heather unless you've met her and stepped into her aura. Heather is an actress through and through and, though you may not understand what she's trying to teach you sometimes, just bathe in her light and she'll lead the way.
Caring, amazing, knowledgable, inspiring......
I love Heather. She is such a great teacher, and the class  was so amazing and inspirational. Acting has always been a passion of mine, but Heather turned it into something more than that.
she is great
Heather is a goddess. She wants all of her students to succeed and she genuinely cares about every person in the class and their general well being in addition to their academic/theatrical success.
Great teacher!!! Aso very HOT!!!!!!
Absolutely Brilliant.
I worship the ground she walks on. Brilliant, clear, and extremely helpful. Amazingly talented and a pleasure to work with.

Kind, hilarious, and ridiculously intelligent. I left all of his lectures feeling humbled & inspired; the way he demonstrated math problems was nothing short of beautiful, almost like a performance. You'll never be bored. He grades more based on effort than whether you do the problems perfectly. TRY as hard as you can and you'll succeed!

MATH220 is a difficult course but Prof Calcut makes it very manageable. His lectures are fantastic and very comprehensible, and he will do his very best to make sure all of his students have a grasp on the material. Make sure to utilize the OWLS tutor and his office hours - and just get to know him as a person, because he's a lot of fun to talk to!
ratingTags: Accessible outside class--Clear grading criteria--Amazing lectures

comment: Prof Calcut is great-- caring, hilarious, and does a good job encouraging questions. The class was somewhat difficult, but I think that was mainly because I had about 66% attendance. The lectures are easy to follow, and I'd highly recommend going to as many as you possibly can (it would've saved me a spot of trouble).

Jack is extremely knowledgeable, patient, reasonable, and helpful - not to mention absolutely hilarious. He is also a very fair grader. You get out of this class what you put in: as long as you are willing to work hard and ask questions at office hours, you are practically guaranteed success. Don't miss an opportunity to take a class with him!!!
He is really great!!!!! Quite an interesting lesson! But this course would be difficult after midterm... And you should spend time on it! Especially office hour!
ratingTags: BEWARE OF POP QUIZZES--ACCESSIBLE OUTSIDE CLASS--Amazing lectures

comment: Jack is AMAZING. His lectures are extremely clear because he makes every effort to ensure students understand the topic. He has an infectious enthusiasm for mathematics. His homework load is relatively light, and his tests and quizzes are easy if you understand the material. Absolutely take a class with him!
He's an awesome lecturer and always stops for questions. He does write on the black board very quickly and erases just as fast but again, he is always helpful in clarifying things.

Amazing professor! Very accessible outside class. During office hours, his office often will be crowded with students. His grading is very fair. Tests are not hard and the amount of problems is very reasonable. Quizs are all very easy(easier than the homework). Homework is not so much.

Calcut is a passionate and humorous lecturer, but also a TRULY GREAT person. His lectures are organized (has great handwriting), and he makes his expectations clear: consistent hard work pays off. HW is a major component of your grade. He goes on tangents a lot, but you won't be tested on them. He will make you LOVE math. MUST TAKE A CLASS W/ HIM!!

Math has never been my thing, but Calculus is a prerequisite to many other ECON and CSCI classes I am interested in. Nonetheless, Professor Calcut made the class one of my favorites  he is a very helpful and engaging teacher who can break a complex problem down into more manageable components. I also enjoy the *very* funny tangents he goes on.

A very good prof, Calcut is very clear, very precise, and loves to go off on short, funny tangents. He tries to be relatable for his students and is adorably awkward. He wants to make sure you understand the concepts of the class, more than applying them to real-life situations.
His classes are very clear and well-organized, with approriate amount of workload. Really nice guy. Homework and exams are super easy.

Every lecture, we'd go into class and get pumped up about discrete math (not an easy accomplishment). I laughed a lot. The homework and tests were sometimes tricky but I think the challenge actually improved the class, and there were plenty of ways he provided to find help. Plus Calcut knew the material inside out, so office hours were always gold.

Calcut is great.  He really wants to see his students succeed, so his expectations are super clear and not difficult to meet if you put in the work.  He's very receptive to questions and need for extra help.  Take Calc II with him!  He's amazing and passionate!

Took both Calc 2 and Discrete Math Spring Semester. One of the more talented teachers I've ever had, he's very good at his job. Does a terrific job motivating various equations, shows proofs, and shows cool applications of the material we're learning. I've laughed every class. As a side- would not suggest 226 (more so the material, he was fine)

Calcut is an awesome teacher! He explains everything in great detail and doesn't skip any steps. Sometimes it seems like he goes into too great of detail, but then you realize that the explanation of the step cleared up any later questions. He obviously knows the material very well and best of all, he enjoys teaching us!

Very clear, very helpful. Makes well-intentioned attempts at humor which occasionally fall flat. Strives for completeness in his proofs, which can get boring, but understands that it can. I found the class to be quite easy, but a fair chunk (majority of the first midterm) was review for me. If you have a choice of professor, definitely go for him!

Jack is a great teacher and a really cool guy.  He grades fairly and makes an effort to be as helpful and available as possible.  In general a good professor.  Take as many classes with him as possible, they make waking up early for math bearable.
GREAT TEACHER and a really nice guy, GO TO OFFICE HOURS and I PROMISE you will get an A

Really great professor.  Very helpful outside of class.  His lectures and homework questions are often very wordy, which sometimes makes it difficult.  Also, he does nothing about the rampant cheating in all his classes, which is very frustrating, but, overall, he's great.

He's an incredibly clear and thorough teacher, but you can also tell he's just an incredibly nice guy. He posts class slides so you don't really have to take notes, posts study guides and keeps good office hours. Basically if you try you will do well because he makes sure he's blatantly clear about what you need to know.
probably the nicest guy you'll meet in the school's ECON department. fair grader. really helpful in office hour. lucky to have him as my major advisor.
so endearing...clearly loves the subject! super willing to help during office hours. i recommend taking a class with him if you're mildly interested in econ!

He's a great professor! Explains things very clearly, answers questions well, provides lots of online review materials, and easy to approach when you need help. He really got me interested in the topic, and I want to take more classes with him!
great guy

Dynamic, fast-paced lectures; answers questions readily and thoroughly without losing focus. Textbook itself is not required but Aplia access is essential to pass the course - at only $80, a deal, and well-utilized. Exams fair - no review in-class, plenty online and office hours open. Easily the best Econ 101 prof from what I've heard!

I love this class. She brings it to life because she has real world experience and know what she is talking about. I like the way she teaches, it gets students really involved. She cares about the important stuff. And she is really nice.
Not helpful at all. Is confusing and her grades make no sense.
Janet is easily the kindest prof I've ever had. She also does a great job structuring class so that everyone can participate. HUGE recommend.

Janet is a professor that not only gets any student, from a crunchy granola to a north campus bro, to open up and be present; she also uses her privilege to expose the seemingly subtle injustices that affect ALL of us. She is what the Environmental Justice world needs. Someone who genuinely cares about the people who usually get left behind.

Janet has been the highlight of my entire ENVS major,  my one regret is not rearranging everything else to take more classes with her. She's inspirational, creates a very good and intentional space in class for talking about environmental justice issues. An incredible resource, great fun in office hours. She's the future of the field.

Best professor ever. The class is challenging to the mind and to ideals of society. Which is exactly what we should be discussing always. It's a critical analysis of the way agriculture functions in our society and forces an in depth understanding of the environmental justice movement. Best class ever. Best professor ever.
Janet is a wonderful professor. I learned so much in this class, and it really opened my eyes to a lot of social justice issues in the U.S. that are largely ignored by the environmental movement.
the best teacher I have ever had by far
Interesting readings and topics and she uses class time well. Very helpful and nice.
The class is easy. Janet is a proficient teacher, who will spend tons of time talking with any student of any level. Very kind.

Coolest prof at Oberlin. Nancy is clear about her expectation and lectures well. I like class discussions a lot sometimes. if you want a good grade, u def gonna work for it, but the good thing is she'll tell you exactly what u need to do for that. I really liked the class.
amazing prof gives constructive advice
One on one, favorite prof. at Oberlin, second semester fourth year, psych major.

Insightful, caring, and unafraid to share her own work. She gives good feedback without making it feel like a personal attack, and is very good at conducting small group peer workshopping of pieces written for class. (Both easier and more efficient than having one person at a time present to the entire class.) Lots of nice hands-on work, too..
great class, great prof
Very friendly and approachable. Relatively helpful. I enjoyed his class.
I had him when he was right out of grad school, and while it took him a little while to get going, by the end he was a good lecturer. Pretty accessible at office hours, too.
Nice guy, good teacher, bit boring. As a person who was terrified of chemistry, I enjoy the class and am doing well in it, so that's a big thing.

For his first year, I thought he was great. Because he's so young, he seemed better able to relate to the students which made it worth coming to class. He knows his material, even if it can be a bit dry at times. Nice guy, helpful during office hours, and randomly brought cookies to class one day. Tests were a bit difficult though.

He knows little to nothing about environmental issues and was not an interesting lecturer.  He did a poor job explaining concepts and keeping students engaged.  Smart chemist it seems, but not for a low-level or environmental chem class.  Referenced "facts" related to environmental issues that were blatantly wrong.

I liked Prof. Opoku as a person, but his capacity as a professor did not fare well with me. He was extremely lecture heavy, and gave unhelpful feedback on exams. Everything consisted of "good, but give me more." More of what? Ultimately, I enjoyed how much I learned in this class, but it could have been a much more enjoyable experience.

Darko is an amazing professor. He cares about the content and your improvement. If you're looking for an easy A don't take his class. You'll have to work hard to do well on his essays, as he has high expectations for his students (in a good way.) You will probably only do very  well in his class if you are interested in the topics and readings.

A great professor, especially for someone so new to the game. Of the eleven courses in the department I took, his was the best. He read from notes a bit too often, but he easily strayed from them and was able to answer pretty much any question. He facilitated what might have otherwise been heated arguments very well. Wish I could have taken more.
Dr Opoku will take you right into the African continent with his amazing lectures on the subject. Clear expectations and fair testing. Take his classes!

Prof. Opoku really deserves better students. He's very knowledgeable and engaging, and one of the most accessible professors I've ever had. He doesn't give easy A's, but he's the one of the best instructors for this subject (Afri. Pol. since 1980). Only letdown: some of the folks who take his class are slackers who contribute nothing to discussion.
Interesting lectures if you engage and ask questions as well. Go see him during office hours to show that you care about your grade and he will help you prepare for tests and research paper.
He's pretty insane. That's all I have to say.

I don't know how Fernando is in 300-level, but I had him his first semester for Intermediate Spanish, and though you may think he's funny at first... you will soon find... he is INSANE! He babbles, is very unclear on assignments, and puts people on the spot a lot.  Also, half of what he says doesn't make any sense.
Relaxed and funny, brings interesting videos.
Simply one of the more interesting teachers at Oberlin. Fascinating texts, and clear commentary. I really enjoy going to his seminar
Can really make complex ideas clear, helped me understand literary theory, Jewish History, Psychoanalysis and more. I will learn a lot with this guy.
One of the best at Oberlin, deep and clear
Great lecturer, deep and insightful. Seems to know everything, one can learn a lot from him. Explains complex ideas well. Material really interesting.
Leaves a lot for students to research on their own, but really wants everyone to succeed.  Flexible and kind.
Yuk
Ari's great!
She is really nice. Easy grader.

amazing professor who cares so much about students and what she's teaching. a little hard to follow if you don't have some background information/are more of a humanities kid. she is super patient and will explain anything, takes feedback really well, gives a lot of offerings of resources outside of class.
Very good. Why I became a GEOLOGY major
ratingTags: Gives good feedback--ACCESSIBLE OUTSIDE CLASS--SO MANY PAPERS

comment: One of the most organized people I've ever met. She will get back to you immediately with any problems you have and gets assignments back almost always in less than a day. She's clear and concise with her lectures. Somewhat of a tough grader, but she does give the rubric in advance and is very clear in her expectations.
I enjoyed this class because it was a science class that did not require problem sets or dry memorization. It was focused on debates and current issues as well as geological research methods.

Amanda is a great professor and is always around when you need her.  She is hard in the sense that she is very strict with her grading but she gives you a spreadsheet of EXACTLY what she expects and if you follow that you're golden.  Can't wait to get back in the classroom, she's obviously excited about what she does.

Amanda is very new, and that shows, but she is very responsive to feedback. She is also willing to spend lots of time outside of class making sure you understand the material, and as long as you do your work (which there is a lot of) you will get a decent grade.

FOR DAVIDSON COLLEGE: I was not used to her style of teaching in the beginning, very class participation driven and lecture driven without much note taking on her part (no powerpoints and little to no notes on the board). Material was hard to follow but a very interesting class. Lots of esotericnew information. Learned the most in this class.

Milligan is the best professor I have ever had. I had only a mild interest in this subject before taking the class, but her passion and the way she engaged her students made me really care deeply about what we learned. She pushed me to think and write in new ways both in class and her office hours. She is tough, but it will help you grow. Love her!
She is incredibly passionate about her subject and very helpful both in and outside of class. Take her classes!

She's firery in class, but go talk to her in person. She's the nicest. Though she sometimes be difficult to track down, when you get a chance to talk to her she is both encouraging and insightful. If you are interested in the Middle East, TAKE HER CLASS.

Prof. Ritzinger is incredibly knowledgable about Buddhism and he did an excellent job teaching this class even though Theravada is not his specialty. He is a very clear lecturer and is skilled at analyzing the readings and drawing out contributions from students. Amount of work seemed reasonable for a 200 level religion class and grading was fair

He's knowledgeable, clear, and legitimately interested in class discussion. The reading can be dense but he assign everything for a purpose. Some people think he's condescending but I think he's just very aware how much he knows and how little students do. Take his class if you actually want to learn something.

Prof Kalyn did not make her expectations clear.  We did not receive graded material back either, so it was impossible to make changes to our preparation for the course.  Prof Kalyn was also very often late for class so some days we simply decided that after fifteen minutes we would just leave as a class.

Hands down the best professor I've ever had. I learned more from Professor McKelvey than I ever did through textbooks. He is tough but fair; if you put in the effort you will not only pass but gain invaluable experience and education.
McKelvey is clearly very interested it in the subject matter that he teaches, whether he teaches that subject well is another question.
pretty cool guy, really enjoyed his lectures

Great professor who was clearly interested in the topic and generally did a good job in getting across that energy. He could benefit from the use of powerpoint, because his lectures could get hard to follow at times. Take his courses.
She was helpful during class and afterwards, if you're looking for a good teacher for geoscience, look no further!

Michelle is the bomb dot com. She is always prepared with informative, clear lectures. Funny, sweet, and very willing to go the extra mile for her students. Class is super chill and easy, but I learned a lot. About dinosaurs. Boom.

Michelle Casey is da shiznit. Her lectures are clear and organized and fun. Also it's a class about frickin DINOSAURS, so naturally it is awesome (and easy for non-science people.) Definitely take a class with her!

Great teacher, really knows what she is doing. Highly recommend the class, easy for non-science people. Really interesting activities, and she makes lectures fun and interesting. If you ask a question she doesn't know the answer to, she will e-mail you with a follow-up. All in all a great teacher!

Doron's a really likable guy (and such a babe!) and I enjoyed the films immensely.  I think I expected the course to be easier/ less writing intensive, so I guess that's my fault, but I felt he demanded an unreasonable amount of time+energy from us, and was harsh grader.  He also didn't clearly communicate what he expected from us for assignments.

He's a cool guy, and he keeps the class engaged in discussions (even if they go on tangents). He's super smart, and pretty funny as well. However, his expectations for papers aren't very well defined-- his prompts ask one thing, then you get your paper back and realize he was actually looking for something else.
Smart guy. I liked the class a lot, but wasn't so sure about the effectiveness of having two screenings in the same week (gets a bit tiring, though the reason behind it is understandable).

Doron seems like he knows a lot about media studies. However, he's pretty bad at communicating this to students. It seems as if he spends a lot of class time trying to impress the class rather than trying to teach. His assignments are vague and call for little more than regurgitation of the basic material covered in class.

I honestly loved him so much that I now have him as my advisor. Methods II is super hard but it's SO MUCH BETTER than Methods I because of the combo of Pete and Travis. Travis goes super slowly which YOU WILL NEED! And he will answer questions or guide you to them. He's really patient and makes a lot of dad jokes. 10/10 recommend.
ratingTags: Skip class? You won't pass.--LOTS OF HOMEWORK--Caring

comment: Super knowledgeable, great at eliciting discussion, presents information with great clarity.
He's totally wonderful! He's both a great man and a great teacher. One of the best professors in the department.

Travis is a good guy. He teaches the development/youth psych courses, and his MO is powerpoints and lecture with frequent questions to the class. It can be hard sometimes, with his gentle, soft voice, to stay awake some days, but his Dev Psych class one one of my favorites at Oberlin.

So adorable! Reminds me of Kenneth from 30 rock. Super sweet, obviously loves kids (perfect developmental psych teacher), very helpful & well-intentioned. The class is very interesting too and I look forward to going. Not too difficult either, really chill, nice class. Can get a little boring sometimes but usually he keeps things interesting & fun

All of the HISP 300+ classes I've taken felt like a waste of time except for this one. I do feel like I benefit from the class time and that my Spanish is improving. She is very enthusiastic and understanding of your schedule, willing to help/work with you. Not a native Spanish speaker though.

If you want to really learn how to speak Spanish, take a class with Barbara Sawhill. In addition to seeing a big improvement in your language skills and confidence, you'll end up learning a lot about yourself as well.

This was the best class I've ever taken. Ever. For anything. Because it's self-evaluative, it's as easy or hard as you make it (although you will have to justify your grade). For me, it took up a ton of time because that's what I wanted, and I improved SO much because of it.
AWESOME.
So nice and so helpful! It is a completely self-evaluated course, but you will work harder than ever because of it. She really knows what she is doing.

Completely changed the way I hear things and gave us exercises and insight that changed the way I approach music. He's a great musician and went through periods of practicing 10 hours a day and is very knowledgable in all things musical
Aural Skills: didnt seem to spend class time well and we spent a lot of time trying to catch up outside of class because there wasnt enough time in class to learn everything.
Very enthusiastic but didn't necessarily explain things very well. However, the enthusiasm made up for it.
Very informative, helpful, and entertaining teacher.

Hilarious, laid back, extremely insightful - one of the best teachers I've ever had. Initially I was extremely intimidated by Music Theory, but his class really demonstrated the beauty and larger significance of the subject in an extremely accessible way. Always happy to give extra help. Great guy!

I can't believe he's got such a low rating. Not only is he really smart but also very passionate about politics and discussion in general. The readings were pretty interesting too. Just make sure you do them so it's easier to follow him in class.

I'm sure Dixon's a smart guy. But he's a poor teacher at best. He's unable to clarify integral thoughts & concepts. His overwrought sense of self-worth is obnoxious. His inability to structure a class or conversation makes class time useless. His tendency to pick favorites is child-like. If you value learning, don't take his class.

Bernadette is fantastic. She is very friendly and hilarious-  and communicates the material really well. She always speaks in French but does it slowly so its very easy to understand her. The class is a lot of work but not unreasonably so for an introductory level language class. One of the best language teachers I've ever had by far.

bernadette is the best language teacher i've ever had. she spoke in french almost the entire time, in a way that 101 students could understand and learn from. she is friendly and approachable, and answers questions clearly. she is sympathetic and understanding, but not at all a pushover. highly recommended!

I sang with him a few years ago in the Treble Choir and enjoyed the experience. I felt that I was allowed to use my entire voice instead of trying to make it fit into his idea of what it should sound like.  At the time, I had recently transferred from a public U and felt that I had more freedom to be a healthy singer under Dr Harris.

Aside from a few minor issues not having to do with the instructor himself I liked singing in College Choir a lot. I liked performing the big pieces we did with orchestra like the Haydn mass and Brahms Ein Deutsches Requiem. A negative was the voice majors who look at you funny just because you as a non con student do not sound as good as they do.

A very good conductor, however is not in the best situation having to deal with so many voice majors. The choir is the best I have ever sung in, but not fun mostly because of the conservatory students' attitude.

Bad conductor, choir is not engaging, rep is not interesting, he does not seem focused on intonation. I dropped this choir after first semester because I really wasn't learning anything. This was sad for me because I love music.
Fine, no real complaints. Class is fun, not overly difficult. Class doesn't interfere too much with other classes in terms of the workload.

For his first semester teaching, Peter T Chivers (PTCHIV) did a great job. His tests were extremely difficult and made one think, but overall grading was fair. He was also very approachable during help sessions and office hours except one time when he seemed a bit grumpos.
Very Smart. Always willing to help and help is always very useful.
Incredibly helpful and I recommend seeing him after classes or for physics tea if you have any questions. Very nice and approachable.

(This was a critical inquiry class) Very poor facilitation, structure was very unorganized (added a big class project halfway through the sem. that we never even completed), discussion atmosphere often divisive and very negative...also disappointing absence of deep critical analysis- discussion was often shallow and v. unfocused. Very frustrating!!
I don't know how I would have gotten through Aural skills without Dr. Pau. It can be a very uncomfortable class to be in, but Pau made it feel like home.
Andrew Pau is my hero.
Great teacher! Very clear explanations of the material and expectations for assignments, fair grader, and class is entertaining! gives no busy work.

Pau is one of the best teachers I've ever had.  He makes music theory extremely interesting and inspires those who would otherwise be deterred from the study of music theory.  Because of him I have decided to double major in music theory. He's really nice outside of class too. Some people mistake his awkwardness for arrogance. He's really great.

Good teacher, has a kind of wry humor which may or may not be your thing. He realizes that basic music theory isn't always full of interesting material and tries to jazz it up, pretty successfully. He's extremely nice outside of class - I recommend going to see him.

He's an assistant professor for a reason. Arrogant, disinterested and extremely nasal. Thinks he's hilarious, loves it when people suck up to him. Kind of clear as a teacher, but doesn't teach so much as give the answers away without bothering to explain. Refuses to justify his grading. Not recommended, unless you enjoy not thinking for yourself.
Dashingly polite, though imperialistic and invasive. Guaranteed to walk around the room and force lack of knowledge from you. Will help write. Stick your ground and disagree.
He's the best!  I hope I get to take another class with him.

Dumancic is a great discussion leader and will challenge you to improve your speaking clarity. He is very smart and has first-hand knowledge of much of what he teaches. He is also an extremely nice guy and will make sure everyone is getting something out of the class. Take his class!
Amazing Professor! Dumancic will change the way you look at history and yourself.
Dumancic is great as long as you show some enthusiasm and do a little bit of the reading.  Go to his office hours.
Great teacher, really cares about his students

Hard class, but great discussions. He is really willing to take the time to talk to you and help you. He is often amusing and entertaining in class. You are expected to participate, but the work is worth it.

She's a bit disorganized, but is passionate about the subject. You could miss the last half of the semester and be fine, and you won't use the textbook. There's a lot of projects and assignments though, and the criteria for the midterm and final are confusing.
ratingTags: LOTS OF HOMEWORK--ACCESSIBLE OUTSIDE CLASS--LECTURE HEAVY

comment: Although I didn't like that the class was so big, Professor Washington-Ottombre is a really nice professor and is clearly passionate about her students and her work. I would take another class with her, preferably much smaller! Very dedicated to her students.
Camille was disorganized and poor at facilitating discussion, but not a horrible professor overall.

Amy goes on long tangents in English and tends to go over the same thing over and over again in class. Things will show up on the exam that she never even talked about. Was consistently 5 minutes late to class. The only reason I got a good grade is because a majority of my friends are fluent so I practiced with them.

Amy gave decent feedback on projects, but does tend to go on long tangents in English.  I also wish we had gone a little more indepth with some of the material. I got a decent amount of practice in writing and speaking French (the people in my class were generally pretty invested in discussion), but don't think I significantly improved.

I found her higher-level French course frustrating; though subject matter was very interesting, discussions were not always as stimulating as I could have hoped, and Amy has a habit of going on long tangents in English. My French certainly didn't improve, and my knowledge of the Ancien RÃ©gime only slightly so.
Overall pretty damn good teacher. Very opinionated on some subjects (as in, very opinionated on the Israel-Palestine conflict) but overall a very energetic and helpful teacher.

Totally awkward but awesome. She'll call students out for using imprecise language, which can be good or bad. She's very friendly in office hours and will give you as much help as she can on long term assignments. She will occasionally do the lead thing, where you'll know that she want you to say a certain thing but won't tell you what.
best professor ever
She is not only a lovely person, but also an amazing professor. I love taking this class with her, and I feel as if I've learned A LOT.
Clear, organized, and easy to follow lectures. She also cares a lot about the progress of her students, and is very approachable outside of class.

She is an amazing person and professor, but don't take her lectures or tests lightly or she'll blow you away. She never wastes a second of time in which to cram more facts and she is clearly passionate about her subject.
She really got me excited about the material, and gave lectures in a really clear, visual, and captivating way.

Good, clear lectures and tests. Talk to her during office hours or after lecture to see the true magic of T-Paine: few professors have her combination of helpfulness, approachability, and striking insight.
Very smart and generally clear, but not always good at explaining phenomena. I appreciate her slow-ish pace, receptiveness to questions, and how her exams are slightly less difficult than thornton.

Jray is awesome. She pushes her students to think beyond traditional photography, and to think about the social implications of photographic subjects. That being said, the class is really time consuming because you have to spend a lot of time in the darkroom, and is pretty expensive because you have to buy your own camera, film, paper, etc.

She's very kind and pretty organized. A few of her lesson plans felt like they had been put together in less than 20 minutes. If you do a tenth of the homework and are crafty enough you can easily get an A without trying too hard.

Absolutely AMAZING professor and person- truly cares about her students. Her passion and knowledge for her work + current events is undeniable. Very helpful w feedback on projects (email or office hours)! Love that she allows flexibility and motivates students to research, interact, and be creative! I've taken most of her classes- EVERYONE should!
Claire is incredible!!! Every class I have taken with her has been amazing. She is so passionate, smart, and respectful. Easily the best professor in the department, one of the best in the school.

Amazing professor, really clear that she knows her stuff. The readings were very interesting, but the in-class discussions weren't great. Granted, this was probably more a problem with the Spanish comfort level of most of the class, as my other HISP classes have been similar.  Overall, I highly recommend Claire, and the class is fun

I always tell people that they have to take a class with Professor Solomon, whatever major they choose. She's an amazing teacher & human being. She'll challenge you to rethink your ideas, reassure you that you aren't crazy and inspire the best out of you. Sometime's her feedback is longer than the  paper, and it makes you love life & writing & her.

Claire was absolutely amazing. Really energetic and fun, got me really interested in the subject. The class is great, analyzing melodramas every day. We had to watch 3 movies/week for most of the semester, which was a lot, but also fun. Projects were also really cool.
So wonderful, cannot rate enough. She makes everything interesting and wonderful, and I wish I could take more classes with her.

Claire is wonderful and already has a very well-deserved cult following at Oberlin.  She cares deeply about students and about the subject matter, and is very receptive to students' ideas.  She is incredibly intelligent and inspiring, and her Spanish is amazing for a non-native speaker. Also not super difficult (but very helpful) grading.
Claire is a great professor. She gives interesting readings, and she is very helpful. She is passionate about what she is teaching, making her classes more enjoyable.
I did OK in this class but it is no fun because there is way too much pressure from Lubin. Get it done asap and out of the way!
One of a kind opera director! He changed my life with what I learned from him. A great man who challenges his students on every level!

We were all kind of scared of this professor before we started, but he is excellent and he knows his field LOL. Take this class if you want to get cast because he will tell you everything you need to know!

Take this class. If you want to do opera, just take it! You need this class to do Mr Fields class anyway, and Vic will prepare you for that stuff, and help you with auditions and nerves. You can talk to her about all kinds of stuff and she will help you! Some of the papers are hard but they are actually useful later on.
Really excellent for diction stuff
Really knowledgable and gives a very interesting take on art history. A lot of writing work and a lot of discussion which was really fun! She's a pretty hard paper grader though.
ratingTags: Get ready to read--Skip class? You won't pass.--LECTURE HEAVY

comment: A great young professor - highly recommended.
Absolutely amazing professor. Incredibly helpful and knowledgeable. She's a gem.

Allegheny kids are very lucky to get him back, one of the best classes I've taken in both the program and at Oberlin. The readings aren't too long or overly complicated, he teaches his big ideas really well from them. Loved his test format: low BS, all content. Could see more diversity in his readings, but he knows and is trying.

Perhaps the best prof in the department.  Too bad he's just visiting.  He's really into the topic and uses great readings.  Be ready to work hard.  He's not always the clearest, but I think that's on purpose: he wants us to develop and defend our own ideas, so don't expect him to lay it all out neat and nice.  Great class discussions.

Definitely read the materials he assigns for class. They vary in length and difficulty. He is very helpful outside of class, and very reassuring. I struggled a lot in the beginning, but he helped me through it and I learned how to do well in the class. I plan on taking his Enviro Policy class.
cutest professor in the Japanese department
Great Professor, really cares about students success and gives good feedback on assignments
Prof. Vodrey is a great guy, but not a very engaging professor. He wants you to succeed, but he also talks a lot. His experience is interesting but his teaching style is tough to follow.
ratingTags: Gives good feedback--Participation matters--ACCESSIBLE OUTSIDE CLASS

comment: Professor Vodrey is an extremely intelligent man who has a great knack for teaching and lecturing. He is extremely receptive and answers questions thoroughly. He loves the law and teaching.

Prof Vodrey is an awesome professor who has abundant knowledge of law. He is profressional and can always give concrete answers for every question we ask. He is definitely easy-going and helpful. For people who want to go to law school, don't miss the class as your first step to approach legal writing and some general knowledge about legal system.
Polt 430 was fine. Pulled me against law school. Didn't think the class days were very interesting and the co-teacher was very monotonous. Prof. Vondrey seemed caring though. Very professional.

Legal Advocacy was one of the best classes I have taken at Oberlin. Prof. Vodrey is truly one of the smartest professors I have ever had. He knew the answer to pretty much every question that was posed, and never treated any question as stupid. He reaffirmed my desire to go to law school and was incredibly encouraging. 11/10 would recommend!!!!

A great class to take if you are considering law school. A fantastic leg up on legal writing/ research. I didn't love the half-semester long style of the course. I think if the course had been a full semester and worth the normal 4 credits it would have been easier to get more out of the class as there was so much material. Still a fantastic class!
I highly recommend this class/ professor to anyone considering law school.  He gives amazing feedback on written work, and is a great resource to students outside of the classroom.

Very interesting subject generally presented well. Prof. Vodrey brought students into discussions in a very direct way that kept us on our toes. I enjoyed the experience and feel that I gained a better understanding of the practice of law.
Great, very knowledgeable! Good class.
Great professor! Really helpful for people thinking about becoming lawyers. Gives great, thoughtful advice.
Very straightforward, simple, and good assignments.

Extremely knowledgeable about the law, history, and legal practice. Always calm and rational, respecting everyone's opinions. His experience as a litigator and magistrate show in his ability to lead a student through a series of questions. Wonderful professor. Highly recommended!

Great teacher. Really knows his stuff and gives great insight into the profession of law. Legal Advocacy is a really fun class! It's really easy, but if you're in the course you are the type of person who finds the topic interesting so you will get heavily involved anyway.
Josh is really Awesome, everyone should take a class with him. I hate math, but Josh was really helpful and clear and did a lot to help me pass.
Awsome

Awesome professor. Very entertaining and had a great rapport with the class. Willing to spend any quantity of his very long office hours helping students understand linear algebra. I must emphasize how extremely helpful he is. Test grading schema could be a bit harsh sometimes, but the class was well worth it.

Dane Immerman is a truly awesome professor. He had a passion for the curriculum which helped promote stimulating class discussions. The class discussions were always led in an organized way, and ALWAYS considered different opinions and ways of thinking. Dane gave off a warm vibe which made him really approachable for paper/quiz feedback.

I don't think I've had a more unsatisfying experience with a professor. She is unhelpful, patronizing, and if you are ever unlucky enough to have to interact with her outside of class, rude. The class is middle-school level, not up to Oberlin standards, and this prof will make you hate the subject. AVOID AT ALL COSTS.
Super smart, funny and kind. Takes the time to talk with his students outside of class; wish he'd be here more than one year. Easily the best professor I have had at Oberlin.

Professor DeSante is hands down the best professor I have ever had. He is engaging and funny, and he enjoys playing devil's advocate to make students think critically. The readings he assigns are fascinating, and he's always willing to talk outside of class. I can't remember a single class period where I wasn't thoroughly engaged or didn't laugh.

Azita is very caring and thoughtful. I love the readings, and she reads students's pieces so well.   The best part about Azita teaching a small creative writing class is her ability to conduct a workshop--so well--you cannot help but learning.

Azita's fantastic. As a freshman, when I didn't get into an Intro CRWR class, SHE reached out to ME and offered me a slot in Small Prose Forms. She continued to conduct herself with that sort of above-and-beyond personal connection throughout the class. She definitely helped me to grow as a writer and I loved the way she handled workshop.

Azita is wonderful - she's really energetic and engaging during class, and she's also really helpful if you meet with her outside of class. Her classes aren't easy, you have to put a lot of thought and time into your work, but its really rewarding and my writing skills improved a lot.
Azita is intelligent and dedicated to the subject and the students. Fantastic professor, eager to help whenever possible, and always willing to meet outside of class.
Azita is a fantastic professor. The class looks at published short stories to help us with our own writing. She is incredible at leading discussions and she always makes time to meet with students.

Azita's always willing to meet with students not only about her class, but about life in general.  Her interest and excitement about the class makes it incredibly worth-while.  Even though I won't be a creative writing major or minor, I found that her class helped my reading skills a ton!  I'm sad I won't have her next semester.
She is incredibly condescending. She doesn't care about your education at all, she just likes listening to the sound of her own voice. Incredibly judgmental and unforgiving.

Absolutely loved Prof T! Really caring, intelligent guy who gives lots of opportunities to improve your grades. Additionally, his projects are super open-ended, so there's flexibility to play to your own strengths.
Obviously really cares about what he's teaching, and the enthusiasm carries
ratingTags: Get ready to read--Participation matters--Clear grading criteria

comment: Trinacty overflows with contagious enthusiasm. He occasionally regales the class with stories from Roman history and literature, and he always makes them interesting. Class moves quickly--he always keeps you on your toes by randomly calling on people. He was flexible about test arrangements. As a bonus, he's a snappy dresser and pretty hot.

I love prof. Trinacty. I previously didn't care much about Latin, but thanks to him I'm considering a major in classics. He's probably the nicest and most helpful professor I've had, he challenges you to work hard but you can tell it's because he really wants everyone to succeed. I seriously can't think of a bad thing to say about him.

Intro Latin is very difficult, but Professor Trinacty is always highly interested in his student's success. He's funny and engaging, but never shames you if you fall behind or get a question wrong. He makes you want to succeed.

Professor Trinacty is simply an amazing instructor. Even when he lectures, he engages the class constantly. He's also extremely caring and really worked with me when I suffered a depressive episode mid-semester. You really want to work in his classes, not just to pass, but because he very politely demands you to be prepared and thinking.

Chris Trinacty, like Kirk Ormand, is an awesome professor who is truly impressive, especially for being near the start of his academic journey. His lectures and palpably effervescent style in general seem to delight all who partake of them. He also guest lectured for another one of my classics courses, which brightened the day.

Prof. T. is awesome. Super nice and approachable. Can be a tad critical of students in class if they are consistently unprepared but means well. Grades tests to maximize your grade, but they can also be hard (101 final in particular). Toward the end of 101 and all of 102 the homework can start to take more time than before, but its always fun.

Professor T is the best! Such a fun professor who actively keeps you engaged in class. I've had him for 101 and am taking 102 right now and he just makes Latin fun. Take a class with him, you won't regret it!

Dr. T is a good teacher with a flair for the dramatic. He gives a lot of work but grades fairly. He is very nice but condescending at times, which I didn't like. I also didn't enjoy the online grading system but I did learn a lot about the topic all in all.
aaron is the best thing that ever happened to oberlin, why he has to leave is beyond me.

great great great professor. so enthusiastic and willing to help his students. i will miss him so much and wish him the absolute best. he is so passionate and knowledgeable...take his classes and go to his office hours!

He's super passionate about the subject (sociology in general) and finding fun ways to give examples to the class; he shows a lot of clips from films and tv shows to demonstrate complex theories, etc. He does definitely go off on a lot of tangents that aren't necessarily always connected. But he's super friendly and eager to help out students.

Very tangental. It's very obvious that he is a new professor. He really is passionate about what he is teaching and does a good job facilitating discussion though. Not the most interesting course work.
great professor, engaging and very interesting.

Very enthusiastic about everything and obviously loves to share his thoughts. Classes often go off track as he brings up lots of different ideas. Very fair grader with easy exams. Obviously wants students to do well. Enjoyed it.
Great guy. Can be somewhat unclear at times during lecture, but is great in office hours. Very clear test questions, which I definitely appreciated.

This was a seminar with only 5 people and it was in English but he really knows his stuff.  He offers really interesting insight and knows how to ask good questions to get you thinking.  It's a shame Oberlin made the poor decision of not hiring him back.  He is my favorite professor and is one of the main reasons I haven't quit with my major.

a lot of time i donno what he's expecting from us and he doesn't really specify unless being asked to do so. he's a cool dude tho. really nice person. but he could certainly do better at facilitating class discussions, which always take a huge amount of time every class but are usually pretty awkward and uncomfortable. but that also depends on ppl.

He's a good lecturer, I found him clear and easy to follow. However, he sometimes doesn't really delve deep enough into the topic unless asked to do so. My advice would be to ask a lot of questions. The in-class discussions were sub-par at best, but I wouldn't necessarily attribute that to his teaching, more to the general class atmosphere.

This was an easy class level for me, what bugged me the most was the students and their lack of engagement. It makes me very discouraged to take spanish classes at oberlin again especially because it's a bunch of white kids with bad accents who are afraid to speak up or learn about real issues affecting latinxs. He's ok but could facilitate better.

Besides the grammar quizzes fairly easy class. Really wasn't interesting, class discussions were awkward at best. Rarely practiced speaking spanish (granted, that wasn't a focus for this class). Came into this course expecting to be a spanish major or minor and now I'm strongly reconsidering.

Highly disorganized— he moves deadlines and changes the syllabus when we stray too far from it (he changed ours 4 times.) Not good at explaining grammatical concepts. There was too much to do in the beginning and too little at the end. Would not recommend.
Eli is great. He's really clear with his expectations and extremely helpful. His class was not too demanding, and his feedback is really useful.
tough grader, does not do a good job answering questions. lectures were monotonous and confusing
Super difficult grader, horrible at explaining the material. What everyone has said so far is 100% true.

The worst teacher I have ever had.  She is unclear in her expectations, her lectures are long and boring, and SOMEHOW still manages to be unclear when reading of her slides.  She tries to elaborate, but only ends up confusing me.  The textbook is better than she is, plus the chapters only take a few minutes to read, as opposed to her lectures.

Completely unnecessary to go to class, I learned way more from just reading the textbook on my own, she is completely confusing. Went to office hours and she refused to explain something to me because it was a question on the assignment,although tests and assignments are easy enough if you read the textbook.
She is horrible. Provides no help at all. She can't even explain how you lost points on assignments. I will not be pursuing anything in economics because of this class.
She doesn't know what's going on. She reads off a slide, and she oftentimes can't even answer her own questions.
this is the only class i've ever genuinely disliked attending
Don't wanna major in econ any more. Her exam just doesn't reflect your true level of knowledge. And never really answer your question
Not help at all. Suggest not taking her class. Her exams are riculously difficult. I was going to an Econ major, but changed my mind after taking her class.
Gives wrong answers sometimes.

Lectures miss structure and the course lacks a central resource for what you are supposed to know. You must derive most of the stuff yourself in small groups. This leads to a lack of overview on what is usable in later lectures. Nowhere in the course description was specified that this course would be so different from other courses at UU.
ratingTags: Lots of homework--Skip class? You won't pass.--Group projects

comment: Homework is very hard and it's hard to find help. Never explains anything in a clear manner. Don't expect to get in touch with her anytime outside of her very limited office hours
ratingTags: Lots of homework--Skip class? You won't pass.--Tough grader

comment: Lola is a wonderful human. She is neither the easiest nor the clearest professor all the time, but she is the type of person where you can go to her office hours in tears, and she is there to listen and help you through whatever you're having trouble with in class. If you are willing to put in the effort, she will help you succeed.

Lola Thompson is a stickler with grading. She spends way too much time writing notes on the board that she takes directly from the textbook. She does not teach, she reads from the text. She also does not give partial credit. Enjoys having a median of 55 on exams.

The all time worst material for explain number theory was given to us. There was no text book, and the sheets she gave out were completely unhelpful stated a theorem and then we had to prove everything on the sheet with basically little to no help. spoke way to fast and didn't write anything down whenever was asked for help.

I really liked her class. She uses a lot of online worksheets, which can be frustrating, but for the most part are helpful. Her lectures are  also very detailed and complete, making the textbook unnecessary. She does sometimes get lost in examples and end up with a wrong answer from arithmetic mistakes, but normally it's not an issue.

Lola, Very average overall.  Often hard to get in touch with through email.  Lectures could be more clear sometimes, but she does a good job of breaking them up with work sheets and in class problems.  Few professors do this and I commend her for it, however it was not enough to make the class good.

Wow, I'm glad she was good at teaching calc, because she was hopeless at linear algebra: she simply doesn't know the subject.  Was careless and vague in her lessons, and we often had to correct her when she simply defined things wrong. Easily among the worst classes I've had at Oberlin, even though I liked the subject well enough.

Def tried to make CALC more interesting. She was passionate about her teaching. Nice person. Lectures were well organized and notes were posted online for reference. The use of Webwork, an online homework web, was a grade saver. Her explanation of new concepts were alright, tho she confused herself and made mistake sometimes.
Class was well organized, but grading on quizzes and tests was often picky and not well explained.

Lola sometimes gets lost in her own example problems, but is otherwise extremely organized and helpful. I never opened the textbook once during the semester because her notes on blackboard were so complete.

She's SO good. She explains concepts really well and is approachable and really tries to help students out! She's really understanding too, and relates to our problems and difficulties and tries to make class easier for us. Also, she writes out everything that she says on the board, which is really helpful!
Great professor, really helpful and tries to make the lectures fun.
One of the best professors I've had.  She was enthusiastic, friendly, and the perfect amount of sassy.  I hope she can stay at Oberlin for much more time to come!
Without a doubt my favorite professor I've had so far. Helpful, fun, engaging, and an all-around great person. I'd take any class that she's teaching
He argues mathematics isn't about the real world. He is good helping outside of class

Professor Raney was a very kind teacher in my Intro to Stats class. Plenty of examples in class and good lectures. Labs were fair, liked the consistency of the class (1 SHORT lab report and 1 problem set covering 2 or 3 chapters due weekly). Very approachable, only down part was that his enthusiasm sometimes let him get ahead of himself in lectures
Professor Raney was incredibly helpful and his lectures were clear and concise. We did lots of worksheets in class in addition to regular homework, exams were fair.

He is a kind, capable professor who explains everything clearly and thoroughly. Rather than just running through lectures, he truly wants the students to understand the material and is open to questions. Exams are fair and very manageable.
Professor Raney is so kind and understanding. His lectures are clear and concise and his tests are very fair.
The easiest prof I've met so far! Love him!

Raney's had mixed reviews, but his teaching style worked very well for me. He invited our participation in class - something lacking in our math dept - and was an ally to me when I needed help. Friendly. He's not a genius on a pedestal with all the answers, just a smart guy. Class was a commitment, but engaging hw and tests.

Unless you've taken Calculus II before, this class will be difficult beyond belief. If you have, it'll just be plain difficult. His lectures only go over last weeks homework problems, only barely moving on to the new stuff before the weekly quizzes. The only way I passed was by having him re-explain things to me in the office hours.
Best Neuroscience Prof. I've met. 10/10

Prof. Robinson is super nice and understanding. I had her for Intro Neuro and was really surprised at how she actually was willing to tell what she was going to ask on the test or at least what specific areas parts of the test would be on. She had very helpful powerpoint and handouts and I really enjoyed taking intro neuro with her.

I am madly in love with this professor. She is by far the best professor that I have had so far at Oberlin. She made us cupcakes on the last day of class to celebrate being done. Seriously, she is an amazing professor. Her class is really difficult but completely and totally worth it. I would recommend it to anyone invested in Neuroanat. 10/10

He's caring, extremely intelligent, funny, and a good friend. Not like your typical professor/student relationship. Really intriguing guy with a lot of knowledge and things to say. From what i've seen second hand he's very patient and good person to take intro courses with, if french is new to you. also has a lot to teach those with advanced french
Incredibly amazing.

Incredible professor. Capable of explaining absolutely anything in a clear, engaging manner. Class is always interesting and well-planned. Perfect balance of challenging and creative. He's truly an amazing teacher in all regards.

Amazing professor! Seriously, take this class if you're at all interested in learning French. Thomas is always enthusiastic and clear in his explanations - if you show up to class everyday and study consistently outside of class, it should be easy to get an A. Planning to double major now thanks to him.

Harrod is a super chill professor. His class was reading intensive, but definitely doable. Whenever I needed help on a paper, he was  more than ready to help at office hours. He gave me resources for my final paper and definitely helped me improve with my analysis and view of literature in the grander scheme of things!

Aaron Goldman is such a great professor. He knows so much and is not intimidating in any way. Hes very approachable outside of class and makes himself available. This is his first time teaching a first year seminar, but hes well equipped and really wants us to understand the material and not just work for a grade. Class discussions are fun also!

He is that fun professor who runs in to class with bafrazzled hair and welcomes everyone to class excitedly. He's enthusiastic and makes biology fun. He's very supportive and easy to approach, and he does a lot for his students. He really cares about us, and wants us to love biology. He makes his expectations very clear so there's very low stress.
Wonderful professor. Clear, articulate, engaging. Very passionate about the course material. He knows SO MUCH. And he's super approachable. Definitely take a class with him.

Victoria is the best professor I've had at Oberlin by a landslide. She is incredibly  supportive both personally and academically, she is extremely passionate about the material, and she teaches in a way that gets everyone just as excited about the subjects as she is. If you have the chance to take a class with her, DO IT!

I had Chem 101 with her and really enjoyed it. I feel like I did well without learning as much as I could have though. I really enjoyed her final project where you had to sing a song that you replaced with chem lyrics. She was super nice and had a diverse teaching style.

Chelsea is a fantastic educator. She is always willing to help out when you are in need. I would highly recommend taking organic chemistry with her. That being said, she was not always helpful in lab.

This professor is not at Oberlin College anymore, but is at Colorado College, so I am sorry for the confusion. I am referring to Professor Martinez's performance at CC. Teaching the class was obviously something she considered to be for herself, rather than for the students. She talked a lot about herself and did not listen to student input well.

Professor Washington is fairly new to Oberlin but is super nice and helpful! His first year seminar was SO easy but still engaging and interesting. Homework was minimal. I would highly recommend this class, especially if you're worried about adjusting to college life/workload because this doesn't add to it too much

Christopher is the sweetest guy ever, and the best teacher. He is patient, informative, practical, but also is really kind and has a great sense of humor. He's really one of the greatest teachers I've ever had. The course is pretty easy because most of the credit comes from participation. You should take a class with him - it's so much fun!
A curious professor. If you were very proactive, attentive, and respectful, she could really whip your writing and discussion skills into shape.

Professor Vange is one of the rare professors who actually makes an active effort to make Professor Vange's classes more accessible. The content was really interesting and informative (although beware the readings that are emotionally difficult). Largely discussion based and students are pushed to challenge ideas that come up in readings.
One of the best classes I have taken at Oberlin. Professor Vange allows students to focus on what they're most interested in, and always gets students involved in an engaging in class discussion.

Professor Vange is a wonderful professor. The class has a lot of reading and responses to write, but it's all very interesting. She is also very understanding of student's needs and is invested in helping us do well.

This past year was her first at Oberlin. She is the Queer Studies faculty and teaches some interesting stuff for sure. If you can show her that you are serious and need help she will do a lot to help you succeed. Sometimes seems to forget what it was like to be an undergrad when she assigns tons of reading or projects.

She is a wonderful professor but I only recommend taking Intro to Sociology if you want to take more Sociology courses. There is not a lot of stimulating debate although the readings are interesting. She is obviously very passionate about the material, it just is a very intro class.

One of the most Oberlin-centric professors I've had here. This professor grades your papers based upon how much of the cool-aid you choose to drink or pretend to drink. The classroom discussion culture was an echo chamber and I came away from class often feeling like I had just binge watched Portlandia for way too long.
Class is pretty easy and interesting material.  She occasionally presents certain topics in a problematic way, which was very frustrating.

Sociology 110 was a joke. Don't take this class if you enjoy stimulating discussions or if you dare to question any of arguments in the facile readings she gives you. Awful class. Parris is intelligent, I'm sure, but does not like to explore issues from multiple perspectives. A classic Oberlin problem.

Christie is so so lovely! She really loves environmental sociology and you can tell by the way she lectures in that class. She taught my first sociology class and I had such a good experience. She gives you a lot of leeway to explore the things you want to explore. She can assign heavy, academic readings but there aren't many assignments.

I have taken several classes with her and she is one of my favorite professors.  She is clear and does not assign too much work.  She is a fair grader and is generally pretty generous.  Also took SOCI 110, but I could only list one in the description here.

This man would probably explain how to add 2+2 using differential equations. I'm sure his teaching style works for some, but for me, it made everything hopelessly confusing. I sat down for the midterm, didn't know how to solve a single question, walked out early and dropped the class. I was so ashamed but I didn't really have any other choice.

Professor Marx is the best math professor/teacher I have ever had. He honestly cares about his students and you can't help but just love the guy. He also actually makes study guides for you for the exam! AND THEY ARE REALLY GOOD! Go to group office hours, study those study guides. His lectures are really good. Listen to him and give him a chance.

Chris Marx is without a doubt the best professor or teacher I have had in my entire life. I was shocked to see some of the ratings, but I suppose those who do poorly in the class don't want to blame themselves, but they should. If you follow his study guides (which he makes for you) and you go to group office hours, it is impossible not to get an A

This class singlehandedly killed my long-held hope to be a math major. Lectures were extremely difficult to follow. Still, I thought that if I studied hard, I would be okay. Not so. I would attend office hours with q's after having spent many hours on a HW assignment, only to be dismissed with the instructions to "look back in my notes." Useless.
He's a very kind and understanding person, but is also incredibly organized and always prepared for class. Assignments are clear, if difficult.
Chris is one of the best math professors I've ever had. The way he approaches a mathematical proof is inspirational.

His lectures are clear, organized, and easy to follow. Marx is an intelligent man, but he is also a great professor who genuinely cares about his students. Office hours and CLEAR sessions are helpful. One of the best math professors I've had, and I truly feel very confident in owning the material after finishing the class. No question.

Professor Marx makes the complicated both understandable and interesting. He is invested in the understanding of his students and will do anything to make sure you understand the material (assuming you put in some work as well). His lectures are immaculate (as is his style), and his preparation and understanding of course material superb.

Prof Marx is the best teacher I've ever had. His dress is sharp, his lectures articulate, and his dedication to students unmatched. Office hours are incredibly helpful, and you will do well if you do the work. 301 is very difficult and even more work intensive, but the work is meaningful and I would not have done near as well if it were any less.
ratingTags: Skip class? You won't pass.--LOTS OF HOMEWORK--ACCESSIBLE OUTSIDE CLASS

comment: Professor Marx is a very kind man, and a very good professor. He puts  a LOT of work into teaching and managing his classes at every level,  but that means that you have to hold up your end of the deal, too. Extremely accessible, and cares a lot about his students.
A really lovely professor. Very accessible outside classroom. Workload not too heavy and easy to pass.

He is a nice guy and is approachable about things. However, the way he teaches the material is much more confusing than the material is. The process becomes infinitely harder to understand. As someone who already took and did well in Calc 1 in high school, this class was an extreme struggle day in and day out.

Professor Marx is an excellent lecturer and will absolutely always be there for you if you are willing to put the work in. He is supportive and patient with those who don't get it immediately. His problem sets are challenging, but very well put together and a good preparation for the tests.

Great in office hours, really puts time aside for his students. Very abstract, but great at explaining. Tries to go at the pace of the students, but if you don't speak up or ASK QUESTIONS when you're confused you might get lost.

Super tough homework but tests were nothing close to that. Just remember to look through your notes before the exams. Good thing is, homework don't count too much for the grade so do well in the tests.

Loved him. It is true he is particular about notation, but he makes this clear in the beginning. Is always very willing to help and patient. He caused me to take an interest in calculus. If you can, definitely take a class with him. He also does dress very nicely :)
Really enjoys helping students, incredibly nice. Dresses really well.

It's really difficult to comment him. His is really a nice guy, and always willing to help. He always stop to check if everybody understand, but the way that he taught truly makes the concept confusing and even more difficult. Asks literally each steps when doing the problem sets, and force students to answer in his way during class.
Approachable professor, but lectures in a way that makes material harder and more confusing than it needs to be. Grades problem sets and exams very strictly.

He's very nice and approachable.  I think he is the type of professor who really cares about the students.  If you ask for help he will try his hardest to make sure you understand the material.  I believe his tests seemed reasonable - the in-class was easier than the hw and the take-homes were about the same difficulty as hw.

The first math class I've really enjoyed, but the homework was incredibly punishing. I understood pretty much everything in the lectures, but out of class I felt lost. Thankfully he had a lot of office hours. Sometimes he had difficulty explaining things, but always gave it a shot. Gave a nice curve on tests. Dry lectures. Dresses really well.
Must be able to answer questions with the same process he uses during lectures.  Homework is graded strictly.

Took calc in high school and came out of Christoph's class more confused about calc than I was going in. Gives a weekly homework assignment and quiz. The average on the first exam was an F. Doesn't curve individual assignments, just the final grade. Talks about things not in the textbook, so attendance is important, even though lectures are boring.

Tom Newlin is everything a college professor should be. He is hilarious, challenging, mind-expanding, and caring. He has strong opinions on Russian lit, and WILL challenge you if you say something dumb. Has high expectations of his students, but grades kindly and freely gives extensions. Energetic and a little curmudgeonly (in a good way).

Funny, kind of casual. Exams are easy if you go to class, and there's one paper at the end of the semester. Weekly discussion posts are probably the hardest thing about this class (because you have to use APA), but she gives good feedback to help you improve on those and you only have to do 6/9 of them.
ratingTags: Get ready to read--Clear grading criteria--Lecture heavy

comment: Not really my favorite. Ill take her again probably, but this class was my least favorite of the semester. She reads off a PowerPoint pretty much word for word every class, and I found out she doesnt actually read the weekly discussion posts. Shes funny sure, but the her teaching style is boring and shes kind of dismissive in conversation.
ratingTags: GRADED BY FEW THINGS--EXTRA CREDIT--LECTURE HEAVY

comment: Meghan might just seem like a goofball with a passion for memes and a keen interest in her areas of study. But she cares SO MUCH about her students' work in this class. If you don't understand something, she will literally sit down with you in the lab and work with you until you do. She really wants everyone to see how cool psychometrics is.
Meghan is awesome and really knows her stuff. She is willing to admit what she doesn't know, but there isn't a lot of material that falls into that category.
She was a really solid professor, takes a nice critical lens.

A wonderful teacher for Soil conservation. I wish I would have done more to get a better grade for him, but he was so understanding and caring, since I had my foot in a cast to be tired a lot to do everything. Enthusiastic on the subject and environment and tells a lot to be inspired and awed. One of the best environmental teachers at LCCC!

I LOVE this class. He's such a great professor and makes lectures really interesting and engaging. He asks some hard questions, but it's definitely not unreasonable or unmanageable. He is incredibly helpful and friendly both in class and in office hours.  I would 100% recommend taking this class (or a similar one) with him in the future.

Extremely tough. Take home tests are ridiculously long and hard (you can take as much time and resources as you want - which makes it even harder). Grades really specifically. No curves in class. Do NOT reccommend.  He is very nice and does not feel like a prfessor, more like a friend - which makes it hard to hate him for being so hard.

Professor Benoit was really nice and easy to talk to, and I enjoyed the class due to his personality, but the problem sets were often extremely difficult, both in terms of  the complexity of the material covered and the specificity with which he graded.

He's super nice and fun to talk to, but talking with him is more like talking to another student than a professor. He also seems like a pretty subjective grader and didn't always seem like the best choice for Bio 100. I would be interested in taking a class by him in his actual department of interest.
really tough information but incredibly interesting. Prof Robinson is also insanely smart and just interesting to listen to in general. One of my favorite professors and classes

Too much discussion for a 100-level history course. No, I don't mean discussions are bad. The problem is the professor let students organize a whole 75min class several times. In most cases, students who organize the whole class don't really fully understand the texts, so it's hard to learn anything.
Fantastic professor - sparks amazing discussions and is just such a wonderful person to be around! I always recommend her to people who are looking to take an AAST class.

This woman is a goddess. Her lectures are engaging, insightful, and usually fun. It is clear that her primary goal is for her students to learn, and I thought she accomplished this quite successfully. The readings are manageable and enjoyable, discussion is often quite lively, and she is excellent at including a number of different mediums to teach

Prof. Yveline is super kind. She cares not only about material but gets students  to examine their perception of historyhistoriographyrace. At times though we focused so much on ideastheory that I felt like we had no "base" of info. Only one test+short papers. Class a bit dull, but she's a great person. I recommend her class wsome reservations.

Really awful voice teacher. For those voices want to develop but without any good and stable sound status, don't ever concern about her. She always tries to skip the main problems you have if she can't solve them, for making her vocal class easier. She sings no operatic music, the voice herself is not properly trained as a operatic soprano voice.

She's a really nice professor, but she does ask a lot. She's happy to talk to you during office but don't expect her to answer her emails. However, you can do test corrections for one exam during the semester. You have to work extremely hard, but she does offer a mild grade booster as long as you show up to class.
ratingTags: Skip class? You won't pass.--Lecture heavy--Tough grader

comment: I agree with the other comment on this class. I would advise against taking an intro-level/discussion-based class w/ Prof Kwakye. Readings were difficult for a class aimed at con students and non-majors and not many people did them consistently. As learning was through small-group peer discussion, discussions ended early and no one learned much.

I didn't take a conventional class with her, still, I barely learned anything. She essentially made us teach each other by talking about readings, rarely did she prepare a lecture. Her assignments are unclear & she's messy. It's the end of finals & she STILL hasn't graded our midterms. She doesn't email so it's difficult to ask Qs outside of class

Tough grader, talks really fast in class, and if you miss a lecture it's pretty much impossible to make up based on the slides - BUT the material is excellent and she really knows her stuff. If something isn't working out for you, just ask for clarification or help; she takes feedback seriously. Don't expect leniency on grades/deadlines.
ratingTags: Tough Grader--Skip class? You won't pass.--Amazing lectures

comment: Leslie is wonderful! Honestly one of the best professors at oberlin and nsci357 is one of the best classes I've taken. The material is tough, but it's really interesting and Leslie is clearly very knowledgeable (and also super accessible outside class). Her exams are difficult, but if you study and pay attention in class they're pretty manageable.

Most difficult class I've ever taken - not because the content was difficult to learn but because getting an A on tests was practically impossible. Questions are very poorly written. Exam keys are sloppy and messy so even if you go to learn what you missed it's hard to read and hard to tell how you answer was wrong/lacking. DO NOT TAKE THIS CLASS.

Leslie has a tendency to go through material really fast without writing things down, which makes her hard to follow in lectures at times. That said, she's incredibly approachable and helpful outside of class, and gives you lots of opportunities to raise your grade through test corrections and extra credit.

Not the most clear lecturer.  Can get sidetracked.  The subject matter in BIO100 is mostly just memorization which can be tough at times.  Definitely go to OWLS tutoring sessions if you want to do well on the tests.  side note: once went on a weird political tangent that left the class feeling a lil uncomf
ratingTags: Skip class? You won't pass.--TEST HEAVY

comment: Truly one of the best Professors at Oberlin. Ryno is a kind hearted women who cares about her students and science.
